Data Integrity, cleaning and verification documentation for the following task:

How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

This document is to provide the documentation and steps used in the data integrity, cleaning and verification for the tasked analysis of How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Below the steps will be outlined along with comment/explanations regarding what steps were taken and why or results found and anything notable that could have an effect on the analysis

Data Preperation

*Step 1 - Gather the data The data used for this analysis was obtained through download via a provided link to the hosting website. The data is public data and has been made available by Motivate International Inc.under this license[link] https://www.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement.

*Step 2 - Store the data Once the data was downloaded and scanned for security issues like viruses or malware it was then stored in a dedicated location for this analysis project. As this project is being completed on a home computer, a local storage folder has been set and dedicated to this project (change and put new file path here). This is a secure storage location that is currently only accessible by myself and the relevant hypothetical stakeholders of this analysis project

*Step 3 - prepare the data Here we are going to analyse the 5 .csv files for data cleaning and integrity checks to ensure this is data that can be used for the task.First however we must prepare the R environment by installing and loading the appropriate packages so we can work with the data sets.

Note: We will work under the assumption that the R environment is loaded with base R packages only. If you are running this R Markdown on another computer you may already have the packages installed and loaded in your active R environment

Now we need to address the observations. In this next step we are addressing the inconsistent column names for the data sets along with deleting columns from each data set that are not within all of the data sets and cannot be compiled via calculation or formula (observations addressed in the code chunk below = 1, 5 & 6).

Observation 7: In the member_casual column, there are two names for members (member and Subscriber) and two names for casual riders (Customer and casual). We will need to consolidate that from four to two labels. Observation 8: The data can only be aggregated at the ride-level, which is too granular. We will want to add some additional columns of data such as day, month, year that provide additional opportunities to aggregate the data. Observation 9: We will want to add a calculated field for length of ride since the 2020Q1 data did not have the tripduration column. We will add ride_length to the entire dataframe for consistency. Observation 10: There are some rides where tripduration shows up as negative, including several hundred rides where Divvy took bikes out of circulation for Quality Control reasons. We will want to delete these rides.

Now that we have removed the negative ride_length entries in our new dataframe, we should review for any other issues with ride_length that would effect our analysis. This also leads to a further question of establishing time boundaries - should there be any? should trips under 1 minute be considered? or what is the time threshold for a trip to be considered a legitimate transaction.

to do this we will create a dataframe to analyze ride_length and provide a few quick visualizations to show the ride_length by member_casual type grouped by time frames. This will help highlight any further issues and provide a quick view on the most common length of times for the rides.

#First we must create the time groupings for the visualizations as there will be far to many individual times to show - grouping into categories or chunks of time will make the visualization effective and understandable
ridetime_summary <- all_trips_v2 %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  summarise(
    total_rides = n(),
    "0-5 min" = sum(ride_length >= 0 & ride_length < 301, na.rm = TRUE),
    "5-10 min" = sum(ride_length >= 301 & ride_length < 601, na.rm = TRUE),
    "10-15 min" = sum(ride_length >= 601 & ride_length < 901, na.rm = TRUE),
    "15-20 min" = sum(ride_length >= 901 & ride_length < 1201, na.rm = TRUE),
    "20-25 min" = sum(ride_length >= 1201 & ride_length < 1501, na.rm = TRUE),
    "25-30 min" = sum(ride_length >= 1501 & ride_length < 1801, na.rm = TRUE),
    "30-40 min" = sum(ride_length >= 1801 & ride_length < 2401, na.rm = TRUE),
    "40-50 min" = sum(ride_length >= 2401 & ride_length < 3001, na.rm = TRUE),
    "50-60 min" = sum(ride_length >= 3001 & ride_length < 3601, na.rm = TRUE),
    "over_60 min" = sum(ride_length >= 3601, na.rm = TRUE),
  )

#then we transform the data from wide to long to make it easier to create visualizations
ridetime_long <- tidyr::pivot_longer(ridetime_summary, 
                                     cols = c("0-5 min", "5-10 min","10-15 min", "15-20 min","20-25 min", "25-30 min", "30-40 min", "40-50 min","50-60 min","over_60 min"  ),
                                     names_to = "duration",
                                     values_to = "count")


#for the visualizations we want to specify the order of the time grouping for ride duration
duration_order <- c("0-5 min", "5-10 min", "10-15 min", "15-20 min", "20-25 min", "25-30 min", "30-40 min", "40-50 min", "50-60 min", "over_60 min") #this defines the order left to right

#below converts the duration column in your ridetime_long dataframe to a factor with the specified order
ridetime_long$duration <- factor(ridetime_long$duration, levels = duration_order)

# Create a function to format month_year
format_month_year <- function(month, year) {
  paste(month.abb[as.numeric(month)], substr(year, 3, 4))
}

  mutate(
    formatted_month_year = format_month_year(month, year),
    formatted_month_year = factor(formatted_month_year, levels = month_order)

  group_by(formatted_month_year, member_casual) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(formatted_month_year) %>%
  mutate(
    total = sum(count),
    percentage = count / total * 100
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Function to determine quarter
get_quarter <- function(date) {
  quarter <- quarter(date)
  year <- year(date)
  return(paste(year, "Q", quarter, sep=""))
}

# Define the order of quarters
quarter_order <- c("2019Q1", "2019Q2", "2019Q3", "2019Q4", "2020Q1")
#as a heat map:
all_trips_v2 %>% 
  mutate(
    quarter_group = get_quarter(started_at),
    quarter_factor = factor(quarter_group, levels = quarter_order),
    time_group = case_when(
      ride_length <= 301 ~ "0-5 min",
      ride_length <= 601 ~ "5-10 min",
      ride_length <= 901 ~ "10-15 min",
      ride_length <= 1201 ~ "15-20 min",
      ride_length <= 1501 ~ "20-25 min",
      ride_length <= 1801 ~ "25-30 min",
      ride_length <= 2401 ~ "30-40 min",
      ride_length <= 3001 ~ "40-50 min",
      ride_length <= 3601 ~ "50-60 min",
      ride_length > 3601 ~ "over_60 min"
    ),
    time_group = factor(time_group, levels = c("0-5 min", "5-10 min", "10-15 min", "15-20 min", 
                                               "20-25 min", "25-30 min", "30-40 min", "40-50 min", 
                                               "50-60 min", "over_60 min"))
  ) %>%
  group_by(member_casual, quarter_factor, time_group) %>%

    number_of_rides = n(),

# Function to determine quarter
get_quarter <- function(date) {
  quarter <- quarter(date)
  year <- year(date)
  return(paste(year, "Q", quarter, sep=""))
}

# Define the order of quarters
quarter_order <- c("2019Q1", "2019Q2", "2019Q3", "2019Q4", "2020Q1")

all_trips_v2 %>% 
  mutate(
    # Create quarter group
    quarter_group = get_quarter(started_at),
    quarter_factor = factor(quarter_group, levels = quarter_order),
    # Create time groups based on ride_length
    time_group = case_when(
      ride_length <= 301 ~ "0-5 min",
      ride_length <= 601 ~ "5-10 min",
      ride_length <= 901 ~ "10-15 min",
      ride_length <= 1201 ~ "15-20 min",
      ride_length <= 1501 ~ "20-25 min",
      ride_length <= 1801 ~ "25-30 min",
      ride_length <= 2401 ~ "30-40 min",
      ride_length <= 3001 ~ "40-50 min",
      ride_length <= 3601 ~ "50-60 min",
      ride_length > 3601 ~ "over_60 min"
    ),
    time_group = factor(time_group, levels = c("0-5 min", "5-10 min", "10-15 min", "15-20 min", 
                                               "20-25 min", "25-30 min", "30-40 min", "40-50 min", 
                                               "50-60 min", "over_60 min"))
  ) %>%
  group_by(member_casual, quarter_factor, time_group) %>% 
  summarise(
    number_of_rides = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = time_group, y = number_of_rides, color = member_casual, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  facet_wrap(~quarter_factor, ncol = 3, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = function(n){format(n, scientific = FALSE)}) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgray"),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold")
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Rides by Duration, Member Type, and Quarter",
    x = "Ride Duration",
    y = "Number of Rides",
    color = "Member Type"
  )

# Function to find the mode
find_mode <- function(x) {
  uniq_x <- unique(x)
  uniq_x[which.max(tabulate(match(x, uniq_x)))]
}

summary_stats <- all_trips_v2 %>%
  mutate(
    start_hour = hour(started_at),
    start_hour_12 = ifelse(start_hour == 0, 12, ifelse(start_hour > 12, start_hour - 12, start_hour)),
    am_pm = ifelse(hour(started_at) < 12, "AM", "PM"),
    day_of_week = wday(started_at, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)
  ) %>%
  group_by(member_casual, day_of_week) %>%
  summarise(
    most_common_hour = find_mode(start_hour),
    most_common_hour_12 = ifelse(most_common_hour == 0, 12, ifelse(most_common_hour > 12, most_common_hour - 12, most_common_hour)),
    most_common_am_pm = ifelse(most_common_hour < 12, "AM", "PM"),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    most_common_time = paste(most_common_hour_12, most_common_am_pm)
  )

print(summary_stats)
